y recognized , and Soto surrendered his feathers . [CLS] [SEP] Russell , who is married to Soto 's sister , is n't American Indian and agreed to pay a fine , according to court papers and the America Bar Association Journal . [CLS] [SEP] Soto , however , petitioned the federal Interior Department to return his feathers . [CLS] [SEP] The feds said no , because he was n't from a recognized tribe . [CLS] [SEP] Soto and Russell sued the federal government , but a federal district court ruled in favor of the government , rejecting the two men 's First Amendment assertions and their claims under the federal Religious Freedom Restoration Act , the same 1993 statute that Indiana legislators used in developing their new state law . [CLS] [SEP] But last August , the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed the trial court 's decision and sent the case back to that court after finding the government 's action would violate the federal RFRA . [CLS] [SEP] On March 10 , the federal government returned the eagle feathers to Soto . [CLS] [SEP] But the legal war is n't over . [CLS] [SEP] The federal government still maintains it can criminally prosecute Soto and his congregants , so Soto is seeking a preliminary injunction , claiming the feds are violating the federal RFRA , said Luke Goodrich , Soto 's attorney who 's with the Becket Fund for Religious Liberty . [CLS] [SEP] A tea used by a Brazilian faith is to them like wine used by Catholics at communion , but U.S. agents considered the brew an illegal drug . [CLS] [SEP] Centro Espirita Beneficiente Uniao do Vegetal uses a sacramental tea called hoasca , made from two plants native to the Amazon that contains dimethyltryptamine , a hallucinogen , in violation of the Controlled Substances Act . [CLS] [SEP] The religion is a Christian spiritist faith that originated in Brazil and includes Amazonian and indigenous spiritual traditions . [CLS] [SEP] About 140 members of the church live in the United States and use the tea in a sacr