nherit their home . [CLS] [SEP] The prison system argued the meals were costly and would lead to security concerns , namely " retaliation against the kosher inmates " if other inmates believed the higher costs of kosher meals impacted the quality of their food , court papers said . [CLS] [SEP] At least 35 other states and the federal government , however , provided kosher diets to inmates . [CLS] [SEP] After losing before a magistrate , Rich won an appeal before the 11th Circuit Court , which cited " the defendant 's meager efforts to explain why Florida 's prisons are so different from the penal institutions that now provide kosher meals such that the plans adopted by those other institutions would not work in Florida . " [CLS] [SEP] Recently baptized in the Sikh faith , Kawal Tagore went to her job with the IRS in Houston in 2005 carrying a new religious item : a 9-inch kirpan , a small ceremonial sword that resembles a knife but has an edge that is blunted or curved . [CLS] [SEP] Tagore needed to carry the kirpan at all times as a mandatory article of faith . [CLS] [SEP] But the federal government banned her from the building , citing the kirpan as a " dangerous weapon " with a more than 3-inch blade , and she was later fired from her accounting job because she refused to keep the kirpan out of the workplace . [CLS] [SEP] Tagore sued the government under the federal law . [CLS] [SEP] Tagore cited how the government allowed the public to enter the federal building with more threatening objects : real 2.5-inch blade knives and metal canes , said her attorneys with the Newar Law Firm and the Becket Fund . [CLS] [SEP] Also , federal employees inside the building were allowed to use box cutters and cake knives . [CLS] [SEP] In November , the federal government agreed to settle the case shortly after the start of Tagore 's trial . [CLS] [SEP] The settlement included no admission of wrongdoing , the Christian Science Monitor reported . [CLS] [SEP] Tagore 's attorneys described the settlement as " a groundbreaking policy allowing Sikhs and other religious minorities to wear religious symbols and attire in federal buildings , " they said in a statement . [CLS] [SEP] Invoking a religious freedom law and related statutes does n't always equate to victory . [CLS] [SEP] In Chicago , an association of 40 churches called the Civil Liberties for Urban Believers found it too onerous to erect houses of worship in business and commercial zones . [CLS] [SEP] The ministers needed a special use permit , but such permits were often thwarted by aldermen or it was too bureaucratic and costly to obtain one , the church leaders claimed . [CLS] [SEP] In fact , it was easier to get a club , lodge or community center approved . [CLS] [SEP] So the pastors sued the city of Chicago in 2000 , alleging that its zoning laws violated the Illinois religious freedom statute , the federal Religious Land Use and Institutionalized Persons Act and the U.S. Constitution . [CLS] [SEP] But in 2003 , the 7th Circuit Court of Appeals upheld a lower court decision and rejected the church group 's claims , finding no substantial burden on the churches , which also failed to establish their RLUIPA claim . [CLS] [SEP] Defeated , church leaders were angry . [CLS] [SEP] The forty ( 40 ) churches in C.L.U.B. and certainly people of all faiths throughout Chicago are outraged by the majority opinion which neuters [CLS] [SEP] the Religious Land Use and Institutionalized Persons Act passed unanimously by Congress in 2000 , " Apostle Theodore Wilkinson , the group 's chairman , said in a statement . " [CLS] [SEP] Also alarming is the court 's conclusion that Chicago 's religious assemblies have no free speech protection from zoning laws . [CLS] [SEP] The majority opinion would apparently extend free speech protection to religious assemblies only if they allowed live nude dancing , " he said . [CLS] [SEP] At the same time , the city of Chicago revised its zoning ordinance to avoid " 